1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Okay.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:13,000
Okay.

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:16,000
This is today's Thursday, July 14, 2011.

5
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:22,000
My name is Cheryl Manier of the Southern Oil History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill,

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:30,000
with the video art for John Bishop on the campus of the University of Maryland, both more counting to do an interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

7
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:37,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

8
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:43,000
And today we'll look at Dr. Freeman Ravasque and I must say it's a real privilege and honor, so thank you so much for sitting down.

9
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:44,000
Thank you.

10
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,000
Let me have you start if you would, just with the description of family, community, and Birmingham,

11
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:53,000
on the upper edge of your board in August of 1950.

12
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Sure.

13
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:05,000
I honestly believe I was as fortunate as a child could be, a child of color, could be born in the 1950s.

14
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:12,000
I had parents who were educated, who were older and who had been married ten years.

15
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:26,000
And so they were really looking for me, fine Christian people, very hard working, and we lived in a middle class neighborhood with similar families.

16
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:36,000
The emphasis was on education, on our faith, on values, and on building strong community among the people in that area.

17
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:38,000
That was my background in Birmingham.

18
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:40,000
The church was at the center of everything.

19
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Which church?

20
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Sixth Avenue Baptist Church, the sister church to the one that was bombed actually in Birmingham.

21
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Tell me a little more about your mother and your father and kind of your new sister building back.

22
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Sure.

23
00:01:51,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Sure. My mother and father grew up in rural areas and as was the case with so many people in the big city, they had come off of farms.

24
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:05,000
My mother was born in 1916, my father was born in 1910.

25
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:10,000
And they had actually met in college.

26
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:17,000
My dad had been away teaching because you could teach after two years, had come back and it was in 1938.

27
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:25,000
My mother had transferred from Alabama and I'm wish had gotten the first two years because that was as far as they went at that time.

28
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:32,000
And she wanted to continue on to get the bachelor's and so they met in Montgomery at Alabama State.

29
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:40,000
A few blocks from the capital there and they were married in 1940.

30
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:46,000
And when it come from, we tumke, Alabama, which is outside of Montgomery.

31
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:54,000
And my father had come from Saudi-Salam, Atlanta, Lowns County, outside of Selma, in fact.

32
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:03,000
And my father had lived on land that was a part of a larger plantation which had been a part of his family.

33
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:18,000
And it was my father Freeman, the second whose grandfather was the son of the plantation owner.

34
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:26,000
And my grandfather Freeman, the first was the first one born after slavery.

35
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,000
And if you think about it, it literally was from the 1870s.

36
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:34,000
So my dad in 1910 and then he was 40 when I was born and it's right there.

37
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,000
So you have that period very quickly.

38
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:40,000
And your father's employment in Birmingham and you were born was becoming a part of your career?

39
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:45,000
My father had been a teacher but you could make a lot of money as a man of color teaching.

40
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:50,000
And so he left it to work in the steel mill because you could make much more money over time.

41
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:54,000
But dad had special skills. He was really good at reading in mathematics.

42
00:03:54,000 --> 00:04:04,000
And so not only did he work in the steel mill but he did the reading and writing for his white supervisor who did not have a high school education.

43
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:07,000
Behind the scenes he did that work and got paid for it.

44
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:14,000
And then he worked for the railroad and he also did some of the reading and writing for a supervisor there.

45
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,000
And then he worked with the families who were grieving in a funeral.

46
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:22,000
So my dad worked three jobs. My mother worked three jobs.

47
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:27,000
She taught in the day and later on taught also GED in the evenings, math and English.

48
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:36,000
And she sold insurance and she tutored kids and sold snowballs in the summertime.

49
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,000
So they were very entrepreneurial.

50
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:44,000
What you know, stock and bavain fittings.

51
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Stock and bavain fittings. And my mother was at a school very close, shelled elementary.

52
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:56,000
But we grew up in one of the two middle class neighborhoods of Birmingham.

53
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:02,000
We grew up in Titusville, TITU, SVL, E, the other neighborhood of course was Smithville.

54
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:06,000
And it was a very special place.

55
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:12,000
I had a cousin who my parents adopted who grew up with him.

56
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:22,000
Tell me a little more about the rhythm and culture of middle class black life in Birmingham in the 50s, especially around church and neighbors and extended band.

57
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:29,000
We seemed to always be in church. And children really didn't want to be there.

58
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:42,000
But we were very involved in all kinds of activities. The youth fellowship, Baptist training units, you know, the choir, going on trips and camps, Bible school.

59
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,000
And it was just a part of home but it was not necessarily what we would have wanted to be doing.

60
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:54,000
But it was what was expected. So you just did it. You did it in the summer during the year.

61
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:03,000
But I would also say we were in and out of other homes. And others were essentially parents too.

62
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:08,000
And we were learning much about our values and expectations.

63
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:12,000
As much from other parents, that's from our own.

64
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:13,000
What was your pastor?

65
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Reverend John T. Porter.

66
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Now, he came when I was 12. Before him, it was Reverend Good Game.

67
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:33,000
But at age 12, he came back from Detroit. But he was a favorite son. He had grown up in that church.

68
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:42,000
He had gone, gone to Alabama State himself and had the Morehouse experience and was an incredible man.

69
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:55,000
He came back. He was 32 and I was 12. And he was an incredible pastor. I think my speaking skills come from listening to him all the time.

70
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:07,000
And he was amazingly accessible. He spent a lot of time with the teenagers, with the kids, talking about everything in ways that even our parents wouldn't talk about them.

71
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:16,000
And it just made us very close to him. He and his wife, in fact, she had graduate degrees in music and voice from NYU.

72
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:28,000
And so our church was very cultured, as we would say in a South. We grew up with piano lessons and you'd hear Bach in church.

73
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:37,000
And so it was different from what the larger society may have thought always happened. It really shows the diversity within the Black community.

74
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:53,000
Indeed, and I wanted to ask a couple of things. One is looking back. Did your family have a wide array of neighbors, family, persons through the church who had a wide class background?

75
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:09,000
It's fascinating question. This is very middle class. But understand something. The middle class had people with graduate degrees and the few lawyers and physicians.

76
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:22,000
But the middle class also included people who worked for very wealthy whites. It was very interesting.

77
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:29,000
So if someone was not educated, that person was still very polished because they had been around the best of whites.

78
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:41,000
And so they might travel to Europe with their employees. And they were the beneficiaries of the exposure that wealthy whites were getting.

79
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:49,000
And so they had their own contribution to the community in very interesting ways. So we had a combination. Most were teachers.

80
00:08:49,000 --> 00:09:02,000
Teachers and the women were teachers. In some cases the men were teachers. But sadly, if you wanted to make more money, unless you were a principal, and then you made a bit more money.

81
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:12,000
And we had principals in the neighborhood. But so you had that kind of... Now I will say my parents were constantly helping people who were not educated.

82
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:33,000
We were constantly working with kids to get them into college. My mother would fill out the financial aid forms all the time and work with them on applications and essays. But even more than that, because my mother worked on the GED, she was working with parents of kids and pushing families to send their kids to college.

83
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:50,000
And not just relatives, but people in general. And my father was very good at advising men. Women would always say, you need to go talk to them. And in Birmingham, the name was pronounced robust.

84
00:09:50,000 --> 00:10:06,000
You see, I say robust because of Polish professors that your name is not robust, but this family. But there, often my parents served as advisors or counselors to merit couples when they were having problems.

85
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:11,000
So they were everything from merits counselors to helping people get into college.

86
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:34,000
Did you get into the title of the church? He was a decon. And I'll tell you what was significant about 6th Avenue. When they were building this really big church, when we were moving from 6th Avenue and 16th Street South to the Titusville area, more so, in a modern church, because UAB was going to be taking over all that area.

87
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:50,000
A number of the families were asked to put up their mortgages for the church. And there is a wall in the church with those family's names. This is how closely connected the church and the families were.

88
00:10:50,000 --> 00:11:06,000
And one of the great prides of Birmingham was that the Birmingham, I guess the paper, the Birmingham News, is the big white paper, had published an article on the front page of the paper, which is very unusual. The Birmingham World was the black paper. So we were constantly being there.

89
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:26,000
But the Birmingham News published a piece, the front page story at the top there, that at one point, in the late 50s and early 60s, before the civil rights movement, as we think about it in the early 60s, that we had more Negroes who owned their homes than any city in the country.

90
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:37,000
Now, owning their homes meant they were buying their homes, they had the mortgages right, but they were not renting. And it was because of this robust economy involving the steel mills and the teachers.

91
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:53,000
And so that was the greatest proud of any family to own a home. And a home with two or three bedrooms, big deal. And as we, as the time went on, the two and three bedroom homes added on a room, they extra-din, middle class America.

92
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:57,000
And, but the homes were the symbol of the status.

93
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:02,000
And of course, this is before all of the economy, the industrial economies evolving. It's still very well-known.

94
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:04,000
Yes, yes, yes, yes.

95
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:09,000
In that kind of urban context, would you have had white acquaintances coming up?

96
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:21,000
Oh, absolutely not. I had never met anyone white. I simply knew that white children were considered smarter than black children.

97
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:46,000
And so many of them were told that in so many ways, in subtle ways. The first time I realized just how distinct the two groups were, and distinctly hierarchical, was I was peeling back the brown paper-sector bag cover of the book I've been given in the second grade.

98
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:56,000
I believe it alone. And I peeled it back and I saw the name of the white school. And I went up and asked the teacher, why did they give us the second hand books?

99
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:05,000
Because that was such a message to us, you see. Of course, when I teach the first set, we told you not to peel the paper back so I was in trouble.

100
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:12,000
But what she said was the same thing my parents always said. And I've said this so many times. She said, you don't have time to be a victim.

101
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:21,000
Get over it. You don't have time to be a victim. The book may be second rate. You are first rate. You are a child of God. Get the knowledge and keep moving.

102
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:29,000
Powerful, powerful message. Which I didn't want to hear because I wanted- I was upset.

103
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:39,000
And while it may seem that she was being harsh, she was preparing me for life. Absolutely preparing me for life. Focus on the real things and things that you can change.

104
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:50,000
We're back after a very short break. Dr. Balsky, I wanted to ask- you were just mentioning schools.

105
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:59,000
But before we do that, you're also mentioning this political, that's quite the right word, but this message that a teacher gives to you about.

106
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:08,000
We're in the circumstance that we're going to forge ahead with this side of the certain, you know, certain motive practice.

107
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:17,000
Was your house, were your parents, was your church community sort of actively political and say through the racial questions of the 50s?

108
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:21,000
Is that something that was around your dinner table? Did you hear from the pulpit or-

109
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:29,000
We heard about political issues and race matters all the time. My parents enjoyed being race people.

110
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:49,000
I think my mother was probably most proud. It was proudest of the fact that she had been fired in another school system because she tried to organize teachers in the late 40s to protest or to demand equalization of teacher salaries.

111
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:58,000
This is outside of Birmingham, one of the systems right outside of Birmingham. People were appalled that she would do that.

112
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:09,000
But as she said, she was just foolish enough to try and she was indeed fired. But she was such a good teacher that within a short period.

113
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:18,000
This was right before 1950 and I know it because she wasn't teaching long. She got it job in Birmingham City, which was really the plum place.

114
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:30,000
Right? And then we called him the Negro Superintendent. He was the director of Colott Schools for a week. Dr. Carol Hayes hired her.

115
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:36,000
He liked that mother because she was very smart, very smart and very comfortable with herself.

116
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:44,000
And he hired her and she worked there until she retired in Birmingham.

117
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:51,000
Well, late 40s was the time when those equalizations efforts were underway because, obviously, stakes were trying to make it somehow fend off.

118
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:53,000
Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.

119
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:55,000
How about you father?

120
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:06,000
My father did several things. He was working with the men in the steel mill to get them to get their GEDs.

121
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:13,000
So he tutored them, particularly in math. That was always very good in math. He always loved teaching.

122
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:20,000
So he was constantly working with these guys. And he wrote the Negro section of the Bulletin.

123
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:31,000
Actually, still have copies. And they were lessons about life. But there was this Bulletin from the company, every whatever week or two weeks.

124
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:41,000
And there was a Negro section. And so dad, it was one of the few literate people. And he wrote this section, advice to the men.

125
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:49,000
And so he was doing that. And while he couldn't say openly in that Bulletin, we know people are not fair here.

126
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:57,000
He focused on what the men needed to do to support their families. The need for the hard work for being your best.

127
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:06,000
And I think the message that they both were saying to me was the same message that so many black children heard, particularly in the deep South.

128
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:13,000
The world is not fair. We know that. So the question is, what do you do about it? You must be twice as good.

129
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:24,000
You will hear that over and over again. That don't expect fairness. But be twice as good. And perhaps you will be selected.

130
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:32,000
That was just the way of the world. Now the good part about that is you learn to work really hard.

131
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:43,000
And to focus on self-empowerment. You weren't expecting anybody to give you anything.

132
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:47,000
Which may sound old fashioned, but I quite frankly use the same philosophy of the students today.

133
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:56,000
Not so much about twice as good. Just working to be the best. But what I say is twice as good in the sense that Americans need to learn to work much harder than people from other parts of the world.

134
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:03,000
So it's the same thing for my white students. Is it about anyone else? Well my women's students, everybody. It's a great philosophy.

135
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:05,000
We're fans, members of the NAACP?

136
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:12,000
Oh yeah, very much so. NAACP, Alabama Christian movement. Oh yeah, very much so. Very proud members.

137
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:14,000
Your father's college degree was in what year?

138
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:22,000
Well, this is, it would have been something in education. Education. Mother always had, and was education due, but she was always with the focus in English.

139
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:36,000
Yeah. At the mill, about to move on from the some more active events in the 50s. But last question was, your father's age, without a put him just beyond that period when there was active.

140
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:42,000
And for a while, in a racial efforts to do union work inside the mills in butter.

141
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:49,000
I would not know he would not have been a part of no, no, no, no, not have been a part of that.

142
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:56,000
Tell me about it. And you had a newborn in the 50s. It would have taken a while. But somebody's thing sort of become your attention.

143
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:10,000
But what stands out in your mind is some of the first impressions of open social questions about race. Maybe towards the late 50s, of course, your young child.

144
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:22,000
Well, keep in mind that other than are going to separate schools and seeing those books.

145
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:31,000
When I think back, we were very protective in many ways for a long time. That was the significance of the Black Middle class community.

146
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:36,000
People work to give us as many experiences as possible to make us feel as special as possible.

147
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:44,000
It's only when we realize that was Kitty Land. You'll hear even my friend, Kandy, talking about this.

148
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:54,000
All of us were aware that Kitty Land was this great place with the big thres wheel and all the lights and all the children. And we'd all have to pass that.

149
00:19:54,000 --> 00:20:03,000
I mean, you went to a certain part of Birmingham and imagine a child seeing all these kids in there having fun and we couldn't go.

150
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:14,000
That was devastating. We always. And finally, there was a small third-rate little place where you could go and have a party or something.

151
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:21,000
But it was nothing. That was ball with something. We got older and wanted to go to the movies.

152
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:26,000
Today, whatever we call the movie house, movie theater, whatever.

153
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:32,000
We had, of course, to sit in the balcony. Certain places to sit.

154
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:38,000
And then as we wanted to go to begin to go to restaurants or places, we had to go on a side door.

155
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:44,000
All we couldn't go in or we could go in and get it to go, but not order and sit.

156
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:52,000
And then when we went to stores to buy things, we could be doing something. If somebody white came up, we were too wait.

157
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:59,000
And so more and more of my parents decided that they would just keep us from doing those things after they realized the impact.

158
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:04,000
So we, even, I mean, the worst part was when you had to go to the restaurant and there was not. All you were thirsty.

159
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:13,000
And there was a wonderful, quite only, that looked pretty nice. Had a dirty, filthy little thing, lower and awful that we couldn't drink out of.

160
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:20,000
Those were the kinds of things that said in subtle and yet not so subtle ways.

161
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:25,000
We were a cast system. We were not equal.

162
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:30,000
Tell me a little bit more about your experience as a mental school student.

163
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:33,000
Are you percotious from the get-go?

164
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:38,000
Yeah, I was very fortunate. I think I was, I had old parents. My dad was 40 when I was born.

165
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:43,000
A lot of managers, they knew they wanted me. They put all their attention on me.

166
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:50,000
I was reading at a very young age and actually going to school at a very young age, very young age.

167
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:57,000
And I ended up finishing the first grade, just about to finish the first grade when I was four.

168
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:08,000
And the Negro superintendent was in the school. And I noticed that every time they had this VIP, I would be taken out of the class

169
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:14,000
and taken to the girls' restroom to hide.

170
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:22,000
And the reason was that this VIP Dr. Hayes, as he was Dr. Hayes, was my Godfather.

171
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:29,000
I'll be back to him but he had my mother and I should tell you, mother hid the pregnancy

172
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:35,000
a long time because if a woman was pregnant, then matter that she was married, she could not continue to teach.

173
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:46,000
And mother was thin at that time and she hid the pregnancy. She hid me with loose-fitting things up until almost April or May.

174
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:52,000
I was born in August and she loved the big joke, she always loved saying he was almost born in the classroom.

175
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:57,000
He was born to teach. She did not want me to be a principal, she didn't want me to be an administration.

176
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:02,000
She said he was born to teach. That's what, to her, that was the most noble thing you could do.

177
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:11,000
And one day when I was hiding in that bathroom, really frustrated and embarrassed to be in the girls, I ran out, I got a lift from the kid,

178
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:18,000
the big girl who was holding me in there and ran right into Dr. Hayes. And he said, why are you in school, Freeman?

179
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:23,000
And I said, I'm in the first grade, I'm about to grade. And that was not good, not good.

180
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:28,000
They took me out and they'd me go back to the kindergarten, but I already knew the word.

181
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:32,000
They brought me back to next year and hid me again because you still in first grade five.

182
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:40,000
So I spent my five when I was five teaching other kids, I always got a couple of slow kids and working with them on words and things to keep me busy.

183
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:45,000
So it was great enrichment, it really was. I was very fortunate. And I always say this, it was not that smart.

184
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:55,000
No, I just had great parents who were educated, attentive, knew how to teach. They emphasized reading and math, ideas, talking, they allowed me to discuss issues.

185
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:00,000
Any child who gets that background can move fast.

186
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:10,000
Shifting. Did you have a sense as a child about legal affordability in the city? Did you have a sense of the white government?

187
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:16,000
Did you have a sense of maybe what it would measure if at all a child and some measure wearing this or apprehension,

188
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:21,000
did you have a sense of the capacity of police to be violence, or those things?

189
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:27,000
Well, we had studied government and maybe the seventh grade. We knew about well as a name and we knew both common to police.

190
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:34,000
We understood something about relationships, tree and city government and managers and police.

191
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:40,000
We also knew that police were not fair either.

192
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:45,000
We had been stopped at different points and they were not nice.

193
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:55,000
My father looked international much more so. I always say he married a beautiful chocolate woman in here I am.

194
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:02,000
But daddy could pass for other things. He was well, all in a color, but rather straight and curly hair.

195
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:07,000
And he talked very fast. And so when the police would stop him and he always drove much too fast.

196
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:15,000
He talked much too fast. And they would stop him and they would say Mr. Robusky, slow down next time.

197
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:23,000
We're going to have to give you a ticket. Then they'd look over and see me looking like him, but obviously knowing what I was from the kinky hair and everything else.

198
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:28,000
Then they'd look back at him and then at his license and see the sea.

199
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:36,000
And all of a sudden they would go from Mr. Robusky, free when you're a color boy, as they began to write the ticket.

200
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:43,000
So the big joke, he always said, I was the best liability you ever had.

201
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:47,000
Did you, did you and the family take note conversation?

202
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:54,000
Otherwise about the explosion of sit-ins in February 1960 was that something that really...

203
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:58,000
Very frightening because people knew each other, families knew each other,

204
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:03,000
and the Revan Shadows were attorney shores. These are families knew each other.

205
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:11,000
And we really did care about each other. And if it could happen to the most privileged people, it could happen to anyone.

206
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:17,000
And they're in bomb hill in Birmingham. That's the other... That's Bithil, the other middle class neighborhood.

207
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:24,000
Where some of them went to our church, sisters and brothers of people lived on both sides.

208
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:30,000
And the mother was close to all these people. And there were...

209
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:36,000
Literally, even in the church, there was a north side group, and a south side group.

210
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:43,000
And again, the two middle class groups. And so it's hard to explain just how close the groups were.

211
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:50,000
So when there's a bomb, you immediately, immediately think it's right next door.

212
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:55,000
Because these are people you know. It's very frightening. Very frightening.

213
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:04,000
And we knew from decades about lynchings, about violence. We all knew.

214
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:08,000
And it was very frightening.

215
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:18,000
I mean, if you would, do you recall, May of 61, and I would love to see a few of my classes in the Birmingham community?

216
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:27,000
And all of that would have been discussed in church in different ways. And both in illusions in the sermon, but in youth fellowship.

217
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:32,000
One of the great things about my church was that we discussed ideas and books.

218
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:38,000
And I mentioned Connie, or her father, who was a Presbyterian minister, still worked though with Six Avenue.

219
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:43,000
And so he would help us with youth fellowship at Six Avenue either. And he was my high school counselor.

220
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:48,000
And we discussed all those matters. That's the one thing that was really...

221
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:53,000
We were developing critical thinking skills as we thought about the good and the bad and the ugly,

222
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:59,000
what if things were different, what are the consequences of these actions.

223
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:03,000
And all of that was... In many ways, elevating.

224
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:08,000
These things would not discuss as if it was just for today.

225
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:13,000
I was about what should a human being expect out of life?

226
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:16,000
What does American democracy mean?

227
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:28,000
I'll never forget when I had a talk with my principal in high school after the demonstration.

228
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:32,000
And he was being forced to put the kids out of school.

229
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:40,000
And I'll never forget his having some of us read the Rose Civil Disabilities.

230
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:47,000
It was just... It was amazing the way people got around all the bureaucracy when he was being told that he should be looking down on us.

231
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:53,000
When he was saying to us, that he put you out of school. He did something that was very special.

232
00:28:53,000 --> 00:29:01,000
Instead of making it something that was embarrassing, he called the entire school together as one community.

233
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:13,000
And he conducted that session in exactly the way he had conducted the Unicensity Induction.

234
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:19,000
And it literally... It brings tears because he was absolutely brilliant.

235
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:27,000
He was determined that those of us being suspended would know it was a badge of courage.

236
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:33,000
It's a tell me this story of the spring of 1963. You're just 12 and a half years old.

237
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:38,000
And all of this just torn down.

238
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:40,000
Sure.

239
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:46,000
How did that history find you, the Analyst City, in those minds?

240
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:50,000
I think I told you we were always in church.

241
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:55,000
And I make students laugh sometimes because I say, I'm not going to paint that as a picture where we were.

242
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:57,000
So I happen to be there all the time.

243
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:00,000
And I did not want to go listen to these different people from outside talk.

244
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:06,000
I mean, and I'm sitting in the back of the room and the way my players could play Kate Mew was to let me just read my book.

245
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:08,000
I'll do my math. I love math.

246
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:11,000
And so I sit in the back of the church because you had to be there. And I'd listen to a bit of...

247
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:14,000
And you learned to sing the songs and the songs were good.

248
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:24,000
But amazingly, when I heard this man say that what he was proposing, and that is involving children in the march,

249
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:30,000
could lead to children being able to go to any... to the best schools in our city.

250
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:32,000
Now, that got my attention.

251
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:38,000
Because I wanted to see just how smart these white kids were.

252
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:42,000
I didn't think anybody was smarter than I was.

253
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:45,000
And to me, though, smart was not about what you're born with.

254
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:48,000
Smart had to do with how hard you were willing to work.

255
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:53,000
My parents had to sometimes punish me for not going to sleep.

256
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:57,000
I mean, I just wanted to keep working and they were worth it. I was working too hard.

257
00:30:57,000 --> 00:30:59,000
And to me, that was smart.

258
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:06,000
When you work really hard and you achieve a lot and you make A's not because you want the grades or because you want to...

259
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:08,000
Dare to know.

260
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:13,000
But when he said that, I said, now, that's worth listening to.

261
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:16,000
And I said, what's this guy's name? What's his name?

262
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:18,000
He said, King.

263
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:20,000
This is my first time. I'll never forget.

264
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:22,000
I said, King.

265
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:24,000
Reverend Martin Luther King.

266
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:27,000
It was very amazing.

267
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:30,000
And then I began to listen to him and others.

268
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:33,000
And I realized how well spoken they were.

269
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:39,000
Now, as it turns out, my pastor was also very polished as a speaker.

270
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:42,000
He read a lot. We read books together.

271
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:49,000
So we were accustomed to polished speakers, but this man was talking about the next level.

272
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:51,000
What it would take to change things.

273
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:57,000
Because what we don't remember is that while we knew things were not fair,

274
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:03,000
we tended to think this is the way of the world.

275
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:08,000
I suppose it's the way my descendants felt in slavery.

276
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:11,000
It just is this way. It's awful.

277
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:14,000
But this is the way of the world.

278
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:20,000
And before that King message, that message from Dr. King,

279
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:23,000
the thought was, since this is the way of the world,

280
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:27,000
you've got to be really good to get a chance at all.

281
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:31,000
He was changing the model, the vision,

282
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:35,000
and saying, it doesn't have to be this way.

283
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:38,000
That we could be empowered to change it.

284
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:41,000
Very different message.

285
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:45,000
And did I believe him?

286
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:48,000
I wanted to.

287
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:50,000
Was I convinced it was going to happen?

288
00:32:50,000 --> 00:32:52,000
Absolutely not.

289
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:55,000
If you've seen the world one way, all of your life,

290
00:32:55,000 --> 00:32:59,000
even if it's just 12 years, it is the way it is.

291
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:02,000
The best you can do is have hope and try.

292
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:04,000
And that's what happened.

293
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:08,000
And I mentioned that we have this exhibition right now at this Smithsonian

294
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:13,000
for all the world to see done by one of my colleagues, Marys Berger, here at UMBC.

295
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:17,000
And a part of the message of that exhibition

296
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:22,000
is that the visual culture of the time had a greatly impacted people realize.

297
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:27,000
For the first time, people could see through TV,

298
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:29,000
exactly what was happening.

299
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:34,000
For the first time America saw the Fahos as the dogs, the children,

300
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:37,000
the children being absolutely abused.

301
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:42,000
And I'll never forget that first day that I saw that after hearing Dr. King,

302
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:45,000
I said, Mama, Dad, I've got to go.

303
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:48,000
And they said, absolutely not.

304
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:50,000
No way.

305
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:52,000
And I did something you just did not do.

306
00:33:52,000 --> 00:33:55,000
I said then, you guys are hypocrites.

307
00:33:55,000 --> 00:33:58,000
Well, you see, that may not sound like a big deal today,

308
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:01,000
but at that time you did not say disrespect for things to your parents.

309
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:03,000
My dad could not believe I said that.

310
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:05,000
He said, go to your room.

311
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:07,000
And stay there.

312
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:11,000
And it was the next morning that they had been up all night.

313
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:14,000
After that being up all night, they came in and said, I could go.

314
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:19,000
Now I tell my students all the time, by this point,

315
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:21,000
while I thought my parents were unfair, because my part was,

316
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:23,000
you've made me go to all these meetings.

317
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:24,000
I hear all this stuff.

318
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:26,000
You tell me to think for myself.

319
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:27,000
I'm thinking for myself.

320
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:28,000
I want to do the right thing.

321
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:30,000
I want to do what Dr. King, somebody you say you admire,

322
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:33,000
wants me to do, and yet you're saying no.

323
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:35,000
And they came in to explain.

324
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:38,000
It wasn't that they didn't trust me.

325
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:41,000
They did not trust me to be in that jail with those white people

326
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:43,000
who didn't care about our children, about black children.

327
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:45,000
And they said, you're our treasure.

328
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:47,000
We don't trust you to them.

329
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:49,000
And I understand it now.

330
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:52,000
I often ask myself, would I have allowed my child to go?

331
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:53,000
I'm not sure I would have.

332
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:55,000
But somehow they came in.

333
00:34:55,000 --> 00:34:56,000
They had been praying.

334
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:58,000
Literally their eyes were red.

335
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:01,000
And we prayed together and we cried.

336
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:04,000
Now I was crying because I was worried about them, worried about me.

337
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:07,000
But great, Frank, all of a sudden I'd get really frightened.

338
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:08,000
I was like, oh my god.

339
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:13,000
And my cousin, who was in the other bed, was laughing

340
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:16,000
because he said, no way about letting those dogs bite me.

341
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:17,000
I am not going.

342
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:19,000
He was two years old and he said,

343
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:22,000
for him to give me stupidity he wants to.

344
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:24,000
So it wasn't that I was that courageous.

345
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:25,000
I did believe in the cause.

346
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:28,000
I had said I was going to go and I couldn't back out.

347
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:29,000
Let's just be honest about it.

348
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:31,000
I wanted to go, but I was frightened.

349
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:33,000
And this is what happens to people so often, right?

350
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:37,000
And because I was in a higher grade and kids,

351
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:40,000
below 14, went to the juvenile place.

352
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:42,000
They chose me.

353
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:45,000
And because I was asking a lot of questions in the little training session,

354
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:47,000
it chose me to lead a group of kids.

355
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:51,000
And I learned what that meant.

356
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:55,000
You were singing the songs, the leading people and singing the songs.

357
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:58,000
And you're keeping the kids from focusing on the police officers.

358
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:03,000
Because the police officers were training to try to upset us.

359
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:08,000
And if you ask any black kid, probably the white kid too.

360
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:14,000
Who is the one person that you really don't want anybody

361
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:16,000
talking about your mother?

362
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:18,000
And what were they doing?

363
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:19,000
Oh yeah.

364
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:21,000
Oh yeah, they were just trying to upset us.

365
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:24,000
Because if they could show that we were throwing rocks

366
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:27,000
or doing something about it, then they'd be justified

367
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:29,000
in using the club or whatever.

368
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:31,000
But if we were just walking along,

369
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:34,000
it would be very hard to justify the violence.

370
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:40,000
We're back on that trip.

371
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:43,000
I'm a friend of the basketball team.

372
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:46,000
Let me ask you to even shift to a level of deeper, deeper, deeper.

373
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:47,000
Sure, sure.

374
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:50,000
That story of, I'm so interested in that sort of,

375
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:52,000
that not at home, but that.

376
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:53,000
Yeah.

377
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:55,000
Very difficult to look at, maybe.

378
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:57,000
And quite understandable.

379
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:00,000
You mentioned that you would be drawn in as a leader of a student training group.

380
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:03,000
And I love the training.

381
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:06,000
Can you stay at kind of that level of a sale and walk me through

382
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:09,000
how you entered in what you've already seen in the streets,

383
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:11,000
what was happening, where you had these meetings.

384
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:14,000
Yes, the training meetings were at 670 Baptist.

385
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:17,000
My church, which was the sister church.

386
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:20,000
And we'd be bust over to the other place.

387
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:24,000
And different people were telling us things to expect.

388
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:30,000
That some of the younger kids would get upset and become homesick.

389
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:35,000
We had to work to keep them quiet and calm.

390
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:38,000
We practiced the songs.

391
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:41,000
Ain't going to let nobody turn me around.

392
00:37:41,000 --> 00:37:46,000
And we would, and it's amazing how singing those songs elevates you.

393
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:49,000
And gives you a high purpose.

394
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:53,000
I can still hear all these children singing these songs.

395
00:37:54,000 --> 00:38:00,000
And keep on walking, keep on talking, watching onto Freedom Land.

396
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:03,000
And amazingly, it gave you the strength to keep going.

397
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:04,000
Just to keep going.

398
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:06,000
You didn't listen to the police.

399
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:07,000
You were looking at cameras.

400
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:09,000
You just focused.

401
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:11,000
And I was to get there.

402
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:16,000
And if allowed, I was to kneel with the kids and pray.

403
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:24,000
Pray for the right to be a first class American citizen.

404
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:26,000
That's all.

405
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:28,000
That's all we were asked.

406
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:34,000
And I cannot tell you how much my knees were shaking.

407
00:38:34,000 --> 00:38:37,000
But the songs really helped.

408
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:39,000
And we did a lot of praying.

409
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:40,000
And it was very strong.

410
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:43,000
It was saying, just to God help me keep moving.

411
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:45,000
And we did it.

412
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:48,000
And we made it up to the steps.

413
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:53,000
And that's when this guy with this really red face looking so angry.

414
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:56,000
Looked out at me and said, well, you want a little nigger.

415
00:38:56,000 --> 00:38:57,000
Oh, God.

416
00:38:57,000 --> 00:38:59,000
I was so scared.

417
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:08,000
And I looked up at him and I said, so not serve, but so we want to kneel and pray.

418
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:09,000
And he was so angry.

419
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:10,000
He spat on me.

420
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:11,000
I would never forget it.

421
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:14,000
He spat in my face.

422
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:16,000
Pick me up and threw me in.

423
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:19,000
And they came and got the kids and they threw us into the paddy wagon.

424
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:20,000
You want to step so?

425
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:21,000
City Hall.

426
00:39:21,000 --> 00:39:22,000
Right.

427
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:24,000
16th Street right there.

428
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:26,000
And it was just awful.

429
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:27,000
It was awful.

430
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:30,000
I was on a date.

431
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:32,000
Just in a day.

432
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:33,000
Take to the note.

433
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:34,000
Nope.

434
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:42,000
And another juvenile place with bars and big war fence.

435
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:44,000
And it put us in with the bad boys.

436
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:47,000
You know, and it was awful.

437
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:50,000
Before we got stayed five days.

438
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:51,000
It was awful.

439
00:39:51,000 --> 00:39:54,000
But I was helping eight and nine years.

440
00:39:54,000 --> 00:40:00,000
And a lot of the kids were not from middle class homes.

441
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:10,000
And I was just going to keep that thought that what we were doing was not universally accepted as the right thing to do.

442
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:15,000
There were many of my teachers and others and neighbors who felt kids should be in school.

443
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:17,000
Now who could argue with that?

444
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:20,000
So this was an experiment.

445
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:25,000
And when people say, well, you bothered that others were not agreeing, no.

446
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:27,000
No, my parents understood.

447
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:33,000
My teachers had been told, suddenly through the Board of Education, that the children of teachers,

448
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:40,000
if children of teachers went to jail, those teachers would lose their jobs.

449
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:42,000
The mother had lost it out before.

450
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:45,000
I should always believe God will provide.

451
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:51,000
But so they were and we end up in told people with mortgages and banks.

452
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:54,000
Mike, you know, it was your call.

453
00:40:54,000 --> 00:40:56,000
It was amazing.

454
00:40:56,000 --> 00:40:57,000
We might lose homes.

455
00:40:57,000 --> 00:40:58,000
You just didn't know.

456
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:05,000
So you could understand people who had something already invested, not wanting to give that up for an experiment.

457
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:09,000
And so there were a few of us from the middle class neighborhood.

458
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:10,000
But not many.

459
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:12,000
Most of the kids were from the projects.

460
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:14,000
Understandably.

461
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:16,000
What is it that families have to lose?

462
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:18,000
Understandable.

463
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:30,000
But I think the advantage of that middle class situation was we had just a bit more exposure and could be supportive of other kids.

464
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:32,000
And those five days, did you see your parents?

465
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:33,000
No.

466
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:34,000
Could not. They would not allow parents.

467
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:35,000
No.

468
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:36,000
No.

469
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:41,000
There were, I remember that somehow there were bibles there though.

470
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:45,000
And when, and I was not the kind of kid who could protect kids physically.

471
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:47,000
It really was a fat math nerd.

472
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:51,000
Not chubby little kid loving blueberry pie math.

473
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:52,000
All right. That was my life.

474
00:41:52,000 --> 00:41:55,000
I mean, heaven for me was eating some pie and doing math problems.

475
00:41:55,000 --> 00:41:57,000
And bad boys.

476
00:41:57,000 --> 00:42:01,000
And they were being encouraged to harass and beat up kids.

477
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:05,000
And the way I kept my kids, they always be with me.

478
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:07,000
Trying to keep them from crying.

479
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:12,000
But there were times when bad boys were coming out of direction and I'd start reading aloud from the Bible.

480
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:14,000
And I was like, this is my shepherd.

481
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:15,000
I showed that one.

482
00:42:15,000 --> 00:42:17,000
And it always get the hell out of them.

483
00:42:17,000 --> 00:42:18,000
And they would move back.

484
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:19,000
It was powerful.

485
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:20,000
It was great.

486
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:22,000
And I would just say, thank you so much.

487
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:25,000
Because I couldn't, I didn't know to fight.

488
00:42:25,000 --> 00:42:26,000
That was not my life.

489
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:27,000
It just was.

490
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:32,000
But, and fortunately, there was a bad boy in there who had been in my mother's class.

491
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:36,000
And he was also very supportive of me when he realized what my name was.

492
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:37,000
I'll never forget that.

493
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:38,000
It really did help.

494
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:39,000
Yeah.

495
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:41,000
And that was that was that experience.

496
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:49,000
But the experience taught me was that even children can make decisions that can have an impact on the rest of their lives.

497
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:52,000
And the children know the difference between right and wrong.

498
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:56,000
And the children can suffer and be better for the suffering.

499
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:58,000
It wasn't awful experience.

500
00:42:58,000 --> 00:42:59,000
It was so depressing.

501
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:01,000
It was, we were in the dark.

502
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:03,000
They let us out for an hour or two a day.

503
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:05,000
But it was just, it was gloomy.

504
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:09,000
These guards were always trying to make us feel worse.

505
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:12,000
And you'd hear them in there.

506
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:14,000
And you'd hear kids hollering.

507
00:43:14,000 --> 00:43:16,000
You never knew what was going on.

508
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:22,000
It was, it was awful when I think back on it.

509
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:33,000
But one of those days when, maybe after three days or so, and families wanted to get their kids out, and Dr. King was saying, wait, he came with the parents.

510
00:43:33,000 --> 00:43:36,000
And they were all outside.

511
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:40,000
And we were looking through the bars.

512
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:43,000
And they were singing the songs.

513
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:44,000
And he spoke.

514
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:54,000
And he said, what you do this day will have an impact on children getting going.

515
00:43:54,000 --> 00:43:56,000
I never forget that.

516
00:43:56,000 --> 00:43:58,000
I didn't even understand it.

517
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:01,000
But I knew it was powerful.

518
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:04,000
Powerful, very powerful.

519
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:12,000
And there are a nerds that are still raw, just from looking at the faces of the children, trying to understand what does that mean.

520
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:13,000
Powerful.

521
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:16,000
So what happens when you come out on the fifth day?

522
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:19,000
Oh God, you see your parents.

523
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:29,000
Wow, being a bright son, you realize how much we take freedom for granted.

524
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:30,000
We all do.

525
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:33,000
Just being able to go outside and walk around.

526
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:35,000
You really get to see what prisoners go through.

527
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:36,000
Oh my goodness.

528
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:41,000
Oh, just the freedom to do whatever you want to do.

529
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:43,000
Go to the store.

530
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:44,000
It was amazing.

531
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:45,000
It really was.

532
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:46,000
And I wanted to get back to school.

533
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:47,000
I was an A student.

534
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:49,000
I wanted to be in school.

535
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:55,000
And I'll never forget that as soon as we got back to school.

536
00:44:55,000 --> 00:44:57,000
Well, I'll never forget.

537
00:44:57,000 --> 00:44:58,000
We got back to school.

538
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:00,000
Within a day, we were back there.

539
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:03,000
And that's when the notice came.

540
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:04,000
We had to be suspended.

541
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:06,000
Oh, and suspension was like an embarrassment.

542
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:13,000
And that's why I say what the principal did made such a difference.

543
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:14,000
You were at what school?

544
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:15,000
Oldman High School.

545
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:16,000
At the principal was.

546
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:18,000
The principal was George C. Bell.

547
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:22,000
The reason the person who is most responsible for my becoming a mathematician.

548
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:23,000
He was a mathematician.

549
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:28,000
He was a brilliant guy of small statue and a big booming voice.

550
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:32,000
And when George Bell, Mr. Bell, spoke everybody listened.

551
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:36,000
And when a kid was not doing the right thing and he would boom down the hall,

552
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:39,000
that kid, I don't care how big would straighten up immediately.

553
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:41,000
But he was absolutely brilliant.

554
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:49,000
All right, just so happens that George Bell is the uncle of Alma Vivian Powell.

555
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:56,000
And my high school counselor, Reverend Rice, was of course the father of Condi Rice.

556
00:45:56,000 --> 00:46:01,000
And so it was an amazing school with very smart teachers.

557
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:08,000
And a lot of kids who were very high achievers.

558
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:14,000
What was your, as those next few weeks to the end of May, on the day,

559
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:17,000
when you were in the middle of March,

560
00:46:17,000 --> 00:46:23,000
finally, the children's come to the city actually a very hot period of a day.

561
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:24,000
Yes.

562
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:30,000
And I should tell you academically, Mr. Bell had worked quietly with teachers

563
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:34,000
to find ways to make sure kids could get homework at home.

564
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:37,000
This is really.

565
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:40,000
But what I will tell you is it was a very difficult period.

566
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:47,000
And what I remember is finally having the federal courts

567
00:46:47,000 --> 00:46:50,000
to say put those children back in school.

568
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:53,000
And you can check this, but I'm almost sure the name, the guy's name was I write,

569
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:56,000
the guy's name I believe was Judge Black.

570
00:46:56,000 --> 00:46:59,000
And we were in church when the news game.

571
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:04,000
And oh, just amazing.

572
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:06,000
You want to go like a victory?

573
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:07,000
Oh God.

574
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:09,000
Everybody cry.

575
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:18,000
It was just to know that somebody white in power knew that we were not wrong

576
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:20,000
and cared about children.

577
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:26,000
Just knowing that there was decency among white, made of big bits.

578
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:27,000
What are you doing?

579
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:28,000
Yeah.

580
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:32,000
Did you see anything else in the period that was like single time your arrested?

581
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:34,000
Oh yeah, yeah, very much so.

582
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:35,000
Yeah.

583
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:42,000
Did you see the witness other things that remained as just this flashing images

584
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:46,000
that just come to you when you think back on this stuff?

585
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:47,000
Oh my God.

586
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:55,000
It was that fall in September when, oh God, the flashes of the hand and the ring.

587
00:47:55,000 --> 00:48:03,000
I mean, when one of my friends, when we were in church in September,

588
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:09,000
and things had begun to have signs of hope of opening up in Birmingham.

589
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:15,000
Remember all of the richness of my community, richness in terms of love and spirituality

590
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:18,000
and hard work and mutual support.

591
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:21,000
But you go downtown, I would go downtown.

592
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:29,000
I never saw one black in a position of power in downtown Birmingham.

593
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:34,000
Not even behind a cash register, little owner policeman or a farmer.

594
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:39,000
Nobody, everybody in any level of power was white.

595
00:48:39,000 --> 00:48:47,000
And to have the city fathers deciding to compromise with Dr. King in the group

596
00:48:47,000 --> 00:48:52,000
was a major victory and we said things have changed.

597
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:56,000
And we're in church that Sunday, September.

598
00:48:56,000 --> 00:49:05,000
And all of a sudden, Pastor gets a note at the pulpit.

599
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:14,000
He stops preaching and tells us that that of a church, our sister church,

600
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:21,000
where relatives and sons and daughters and fathers and mothers have been born.

601
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:24,000
And didn't know how bad it was.

602
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:27,000
It was just a shock.

603
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:30,000
And he said, please don't rush out.

604
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:34,000
But it was the first time we'd ever seen church stop in the middle.

605
00:49:34,000 --> 00:49:35,000
It had to be bad.

606
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:38,000
People started driving in that direction.

607
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:40,000
Mother and father took us home.

608
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:44,000
Because we didn't know whether that meant the next church was going to be born or whatever.

609
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:54,000
And as it turns out, I thought back to different friends.

610
00:49:54,000 --> 00:49:57,000
One of whom was Cynthia.

611
00:49:57,000 --> 00:50:06,000
And I'd seen her on Friday and I've said this before, I remember so well.

612
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:11,000
She was always very kind to me because I was younger than other classmates.

613
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:13,000
She was always very nice to me.

614
00:50:13,000 --> 00:50:16,000
So that was 12, she was 14.

615
00:50:16,000 --> 00:50:23,000
And she said, bye, Franklin.

616
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:25,000
Oh God, we said bye.

617
00:50:25,000 --> 00:50:35,000
And it seems to me that she who said to you Monday.

618
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:38,000
And I knew she went to that church and mentioned so all these names.

619
00:50:38,000 --> 00:50:42,000
And she was one of them, but I saw her face there at school.

620
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:53,000
And when one of the girls had been given a ring that morning by her father,

621
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:58,000
and they were not able to find her and then found that hand.

622
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:03,000
And we all, everybody knew that hand was that ring.

623
00:51:03,000 --> 00:51:07,000
We had nightmares for years.

624
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:10,000
It was like war.

625
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:14,000
It was just awful.

626
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:21,000
My parents said to me when I asked if I could go to the funeral.

627
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:23,000
I could.

628
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:26,000
And I'll never forget.

629
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:28,000
I was to leave school.

630
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:30,000
My parents had given me and noticed.

631
00:51:30,000 --> 00:51:32,000
And my principal saw me.

632
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:35,000
And this is education at best.

633
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:40,000
He came up to me and he said, you're representing us today.

634
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:42,000
And he looked at my tie.

635
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:45,000
And it was not dark enough.

636
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:48,000
Now you really was where dark ties to the venerals.

637
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:53,000
And he took his towel.

638
00:51:53,000 --> 00:51:55,000
And took my towel.

639
00:51:55,000 --> 00:51:59,000
He tied his tie.

640
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:03,000
It was amazing.

641
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:08,000
The small things people can do to make a child feel special.

642
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:15,000
And I'll never forget the three coffins with the nieces, the youngest of the three.

643
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:18,000
I think she was 11, McNair, in the middle, smaller.

644
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:21,000
I've never seen a coffin that small.

645
00:52:21,000 --> 00:52:23,000
That small.

646
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:24,000
It was awful.

647
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:28,000
It was just awful.

648
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:32,000
And Dr. King said, what you know, he said,

649
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:37,000
life, I mean, what you need to know is that people who were the nieces were

650
00:52:37,000 --> 00:52:42,000
saying that church was bombed, those girls were in those coffins because we went to jail.

651
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:45,000
We upset things.

652
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:46,000
And that's what happens.

653
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:51,000
And they tried to tell us how mean spirit and how awful people can be.

654
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:54,000
These were blacks, saying that.

655
00:52:54,000 --> 00:52:58,000
And here's Dr. King back, taking responsibility.

656
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:08,000
And he looked into the faces of those parents and said, life is as hard as steel.

657
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:10,000
It's hard to see it.

658
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:12,000
In other words, I don't know what to say.

659
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:15,000
It is just so hard for all of us.

660
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:16,000
I just remember that.

661
00:53:16,000 --> 00:53:17,000
I do.

662
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:19,000
I really do.

663
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:23,000
And I'll tell you what gave me hope in the midst of the darkness.

664
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:27,000
It was the first time I'd seen white too much of it.

665
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:34,000
There were rabbis and priests and Baptist ministers from...

666
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:39,000
Hmm.

667
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:41,000
Amazing.

668
00:53:41,000 --> 00:53:45,000
And they...

669
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:50,000
Can you...

670
00:53:50,000 --> 00:53:52,000
Yeah, give me a minute.

671
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:54,000
Ooh.

672
00:53:54,000 --> 00:53:55,000
Yeah.

673
00:53:55,000 --> 00:53:56,000
Give me a minute.

674
00:53:56,000 --> 00:53:57,000
Just a...

675
00:53:57,000 --> 00:53:58,000
Hmm.

676
00:53:58,000 --> 00:53:59,000
Okay.

677
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:01,000
We're back on that for short break.

678
00:54:01,000 --> 00:54:02,000
Let me ask you.

679
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:03,000
Yes.

680
00:54:03,000 --> 00:54:04,000
It's just so difficult.

681
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:05,000
Yeah.

682
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:06,000
The distance is like a day sometimes.

683
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:09,000
Not like there's many, many years, but like...

684
00:54:09,000 --> 00:54:10,000
Oh, yeah.

685
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:13,000
Maybe this is a good time to ask you a question of...

686
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:14,000
A difficult reflection.

687
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:15,000
And it's this.

688
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:16,000
Can you...

689
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:17,000
And there is no fixed answer.

690
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:18,000
I'm sure this question...

691
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:19,000
Sure.

692
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:23,000
I thought a little bit on the issue of how those kinds of experiences do take their long tolls.

693
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:24,000
Sure.

694
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:28,000
And how you might gauge their implications in your life.

695
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:33,000
I'm reading a book right now where David Brooks, the social animal, and one of the points

696
00:54:33,000 --> 00:54:36,000
of the book he talked about how we developed a lot of the books.

697
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:39,000
And I'm sure that David Brooks is a very good person.

698
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:41,000
And I'm sure that David Brooks is a very good person.

699
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:43,000
And I'm sure that David Brooks is a very good person.

700
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:47,000
And one of the points of the book he talked about how we developed a lot of relationships

701
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:53,000
and achievement is one of the points of the book is that we are all the products of our childhood experiences.

702
00:54:53,000 --> 00:54:59,000
And when we least expect it, things that happen to us as children have an impact on us.

703
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:07,000
And so while we may think that what we do is the result of rational decision making, often circumstances and

704
00:55:07,000 --> 00:55:15,000
previous experiences come together to push us in one direction or another without even realizing it.

705
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:21,000
What my parents worked to do after those difficult situations, what many parents worked to do,

706
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:29,000
was to help us get beyond the bitterness, the anger.

707
00:55:29,000 --> 00:55:35,000
And even the hatred.

708
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:40,000
And what they said over and over again is hatred eats on the inside.

709
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:43,000
Hate the action or the act.

710
00:55:43,000 --> 00:55:45,000
Don't hate the person.

711
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:51,000
I have to tell you when Bull Connor died, my mother called me and she was crying.

712
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:53,000
And I said, Mother, why are you crying about this man?

713
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:55,000
This man was awful to us.

714
00:55:55,000 --> 00:55:57,000
And she said something that was so powerful.

715
00:55:57,000 --> 00:56:03,000
She said, Freeman, but he was somebody's child.

716
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:08,000
All of what he did came because of how he was raised.

717
00:56:08,000 --> 00:56:16,000
And for me, that was an amazing moment of enlightenment.

718
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:20,000
He was simply the product of his environment.

719
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:23,000
And it was cathodic for me.

720
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:26,000
Just let it go. Let it go.

721
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:30,000
And I have often thought about that moment.

722
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:37,000
My mother's way of giving me her faith in life itself and in humanity.

723
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:43,000
And it was also her way of saying, put your own experiences in perspective.

724
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:53,000
And a part of being educated is being able to give context to whatever experiences you've had.

725
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:58,000
And those of us who've been able to do that are much healthier as a result.

726
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:05,000
I really do believe those words of King that you judge people in the basis of content of character, not on race.

727
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:09,000
You can find good and bad people in any race.

728
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:15,000
And I'm here at the university with students from 150 countries.

729
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:22,000
And I've really come to understand what's coming among human beings from different cultures, different religions.

730
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:29,000
And that character can transcend all of that integrity, those kinds of things.

731
00:57:29,000 --> 00:57:35,000
And so I think the reason I'm able to work so comfortably with my students from all kinds of backgrounds

732
00:57:35,000 --> 00:57:42,000
is that I really can see beyond the obvious differences.

733
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:49,000
And look for not only what's in somebody's heart, but that person's ability to think.

734
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:57,000
And my life is focused on helping people to learn to do just that, to think well, and how to act with people,

735
00:57:57,000 --> 00:58:06,000
and to get beyond what we sometimes believe are the most important things.

736
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:13,000
All right, how we look, to move to what, how we think and act.

737
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:20,000
I mean, not to summarize too much human, but it's probably a fair thing.

738
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:28,000
And I mean, this is a sincere compliment that your professional work has really has had the form of creating new ways for children to club and work.

739
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:30,000
I appreciate that.

740
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:31,000
Yeah.

741
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:32,000
I appreciate that.

742
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:33,000
And Mara Haft, so that's the truth.

743
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:34,000
Sure. Sure.

744
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:35,000
These are not small efforts.

745
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:36,000
I appreciate that.

746
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:48,000
I like the fact that this is a campus that really does talk about these issues of race and ethnicity, and works to create a climate,

747
00:58:48,000 --> 00:58:49,000
in which people can say what they really think.

748
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:54,000
If you don't know a lot of people to say what they really think, then they're simply saying what's convenient.

749
00:58:54,000 --> 00:58:59,000
And it doesn't get to the point of values.

750
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:01,000
And I think this is what we need in the American society.

751
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:05,000
We need opportunities for people, whether they are 50 or 15, to say what they really think.

752
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:08,000
We tend to believe what we've seen on TV.

753
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:17,000
If what you see on TV is violence, then you've seen certain groups looking like they're always doing things that are stealing and things that are bad, that's what you believe.

754
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:20,000
My students who are around all kinds of people are far more tolerant.

755
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:34,000
My students who come from areas where everybody looks exactly the same regardless of what race will tend to be far more comfortable, stereotyping, and assuming all people are the same.

756
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:41,000
And I think that's one of the things about education, is to teach people not just about people in this country, but around the world,

757
00:59:41,000 --> 00:59:44,000
that we are the products of our childhood experiences.

758
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:46,000
Everyone of us has some good in us.

759
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:47,000
We can pull that out.

760
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:51,000
And those are the kinds of things I learned through that experience.

761
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:56,000
You moved from Birmingham in 1966?

762
00:59:56,000 --> 00:59:57,000
You were good.

763
00:59:57,000 --> 00:59:59,000
Yes, that's exactly right.

764
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:03,000
Now I should tell you, I spent a summer in different places.

765
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:05,000
Yeah, and I want to ask about that as well.

766
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:06,000
Yeah, before 1966.

767
01:00:06,000 --> 01:00:14,000
I was in Massachusetts and I was 13 and I was going to the 11th grade.

768
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:24,000
And this was going to be my first experience in an all-white class in math and literature chemistry.

769
01:00:24,000 --> 01:00:27,000
And it was clear, the education was so rich.

770
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:29,000
It was powerful.

771
01:00:29,000 --> 01:00:30,000
It was rigorous.

772
01:00:30,000 --> 01:00:31,000
It was challenging.

773
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:32,000
It was hard.

774
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:34,000
I loved it.

775
01:00:34,000 --> 01:00:40,000
And when other kids would not raise their hands, raise my hand, just try the answer.

776
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:45,000
And it didn't take me long to realize not one teacher would ever call on me.

777
01:00:45,000 --> 01:00:47,000
They would look right through me.

778
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:51,000
They would never mean they just, I wasn't there.

779
01:00:52,000 --> 01:00:53,000
It was amazing.

780
01:00:53,000 --> 01:00:56,000
So I always call it Rap Ellensons Invisible Man, okay?

781
01:00:56,000 --> 01:01:00,000
But it was an awful feeling to feel totally unimportant.

782
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:05,000
In contrast to my old black school, where people were delighted that I wanted to try an answer.

783
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:09,000
When they would tease me and it pushed me and they would say, go for it.

784
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:12,000
None of that taught me the importance of teachers.

785
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:17,000
Teachers can either elevate us or even through a look, push us down.

786
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:23,000
And we see both in all kinds of situations among all races, depending on where you are.

787
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:29,000
And what I can say is I learned a lot.

788
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:35,000
When I came back to chemistry, I was well prepared.

789
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:39,000
I had finished the course that summer, all right?

790
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:41,000
Sending in math.

791
01:01:41,000 --> 01:01:43,000
So I was really well prepared.

792
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:54,000
I had experienced also taught my parents that they were not willing to trust me to go to some of the predominantly white schools in the East who were interested in my attending.

793
01:01:54,000 --> 01:01:56,000
They just didn't know.

794
01:01:56,000 --> 01:02:02,000
And so I left in 1966 and I went to Hampton.

795
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:07,000
And because Book of Washington was a graduate of Hampton.

796
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:15,000
We respected Mr. Washington when he came to Bounta Ski, for generations.

797
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:22,000
And it was an amazing experience because half my teachers were white at Hampton, particularly in the math and science area.

798
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:23,000
And they were wonderful.

799
01:02:23,000 --> 01:02:26,000
It was the first time I've been around white and they were so caring and decent.

800
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:31,000
And they were there to help those black kids succeed.

801
01:02:31,000 --> 01:02:36,000
And it was then that I came to understand really a lot of nice white people.

802
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:43,000
And I was close to mathematicians and philosophers and it was great.

803
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:46,000
Did you come home to the summers to come home?

804
01:02:46,000 --> 01:02:51,000
I came home in the summers, came home at Christmas time.

805
01:02:51,000 --> 01:03:02,000
And the latter, and I actually decided after my freshman year to take a course at the University of Alabama, Birmingham.

806
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:06,000
I took the next calculus course just to see what it would be like.

807
01:03:06,000 --> 01:03:13,000
And to see what education then, because some of my friends had gone to UAB and to Tuscaloosa,

808
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:15,000
and it was at all white class.

809
01:03:15,000 --> 01:03:25,000
And to my amazement, what I had found at Hampton became even more understandable.

810
01:03:25,000 --> 01:03:34,000
At Hampton, I learned that while I was best in my school and the top group in an A student

811
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:40,000
that I was not as well prepared as black children who had gone to either prep schools

812
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:43,000
or to very integrated white schools in the North.

813
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:48,000
Now, I told you nobody's going to work harder than I do.

814
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:54,000
And the girl at the time that I liked was getting the top score.

815
01:03:54,000 --> 01:03:58,000
She was a jammer. She championed for the state.

816
01:03:58,000 --> 01:04:01,000
She had had Latin, which I hadn't had. She was just much better prepared.

817
01:04:01,000 --> 01:04:05,000
And so I said openly one day when she got 100, I'm going to marry her one day.

818
01:04:05,000 --> 01:04:08,000
And I did, by the way, four years later.

819
01:04:08,000 --> 01:04:13,000
But I was not as well prepared. It was clear to me that our education had not been as rigorous.

820
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:18,000
I had enough education, though, that I could work so hard I could still get all A's.

821
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:22,000
But they were not the highest A's. That first year I had to work on that.

822
01:04:22,000 --> 01:04:26,000
But I came back to you, and I wanted to see how well prepared those kids were, the white kids.

823
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:31,000
And this was in the Cal 2, Cal 3 course or something, Cal 3.

824
01:04:31,000 --> 01:04:36,000
And it turned out that the average in the classes was maybe in the 60s

825
01:04:36,000 --> 01:04:38,000
and I always got 9, 8 to 100.

826
01:04:38,000 --> 01:04:41,000
And the guy finally came up to me, quite professing.

827
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:43,000
And he said, where are you from?

828
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:46,000
Because I was making 8 classes.

829
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:52,000
I was just about what I came to understand was it wasn't just that the education for black kids was not what it should have been.

830
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:56,000
Those white kids from Alabama were not well prepared.

831
01:04:56,000 --> 01:04:59,000
Years later, as I look at some of my tests, I see exactly that.

832
01:04:59,000 --> 01:05:03,000
But I had no idea. I always thought the education was so much better.

833
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:07,000
No, no, was not the case.

834
01:05:07,000 --> 01:05:14,000
And interestingly enough, I think back we had some really good teachers, some of whom had gotten grad degrees in Northern states

835
01:05:14,000 --> 01:05:16,000
because they couldn't get them there.

836
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:19,000
So we had a solid education.

837
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:26,000
And I had better than most because of the other experiences from Massachusetts and NSF program at Tuskegee.

838
01:05:26,000 --> 01:05:28,000
My parents were constantly giving me these extra experiences.

839
01:05:28,000 --> 01:05:30,000
And we read everything.

840
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:32,000
So that was really solid.

841
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:34,000
We were reading all the time.

842
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:41,000
When I say it was not as well prepared, I had had through pre-calculus, but my top kids at Hampton had had calculus in high school.

843
01:05:41,000 --> 01:05:43,000
I had an head calculus.

844
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:47,000
So when they took it and I was taking it for the first time, they had already had all of that.

845
01:05:47,000 --> 01:05:49,000
Those kinds of experiences.

846
01:05:49,000 --> 01:05:54,000
But my point is, we all suffered because of segregation.

847
01:05:54,000 --> 01:05:58,000
When you've got to put everything separate, different administrations, you're spending money away.

848
01:05:58,000 --> 01:06:01,000
It should have been on those kids.

849
01:06:01,000 --> 01:06:06,000
And I realized not just black children, but white children when I get into the best of either.

850
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:11,000
Tell me about how you watched Birmingham of all.

851
01:06:11,000 --> 01:06:14,000
I guess beginning in 66, it'll be this kind of pattern.

852
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:15,000
Yes, yes.

853
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:18,000
Because you're in college and then graduate school and you're just after that.

854
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:21,000
I guess it's probably a pattern of periodic visits.

855
01:06:21,000 --> 01:06:22,000
Regular?

856
01:06:22,000 --> 01:06:25,000
So over the years, your parents live in the United States.

857
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:26,000
Sure, sure.

858
01:06:26,000 --> 01:06:31,000
I just think of sitting in hell, you watched the city change from that kind of lens.

859
01:06:31,000 --> 01:06:32,000
It's interesting.

860
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:40,000
I saw more and more of my students, my friends, going to predominantly white schools in Alabama, to UAB, to Excluso, Auburn,

861
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:46,000
and becoming connected to those places, while others continue to go to the HPC use.

862
01:06:46,000 --> 01:06:52,000
But I think I was most proud, I was really proud of Birmingham when Richard Errington became the mayor.

863
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:56,000
Because how many cities have a PhD in science as a mayor?

864
01:06:56,000 --> 01:07:02,000
That's it, so much about progress we had made, really did it.

865
01:07:02,000 --> 01:07:07,000
And I continued to know my city primarily through my church, 6th Avenue.

866
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:16,000
And more and more people were moving to UAB, doctors, people in mid school, and it come often to 6th Avenue.

867
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:26,000
And I saw this influx of people moving to Birmingham because of the university, the biggest employer, and well-educated people.

868
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:30,000
And I saw those changes at the same time.

869
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:43,000
I was assuming that the violence I saw in northern cities was not occurring in places like Birmingham, because it wasn't that level of violence among blacks on blacks.

870
01:07:43,000 --> 01:07:49,000
Until I got back there and saw the same thing I saw in cities in this area, I saw there in Birmingham.

871
01:07:49,000 --> 01:07:53,000
So on the one hand, you get the progress, more educated people going to the universities.

872
01:07:53,000 --> 01:07:58,000
On the other hand, you've got the underclass killing each other.

873
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:01,000
Same challenge as your face, wherever you go in the country.

874
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:06,000
And it was that dichotomy that was and continues to be a major problem.

875
01:08:06,000 --> 01:08:12,000
Of course Birmingham's demographic shift, because the city boundaries aren't that big.

876
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:15,000
And this is happening at the 6th Avenue.

877
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:19,000
Yes, and people have moved, that's exactly right, into the suburban areas.

878
01:08:19,000 --> 01:08:23,000
And more and more, the Birmingham city schools have become black.

879
01:08:23,000 --> 01:08:30,000
And before Phillips and other places that were white and yet a few black kids.

880
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:33,000
Some people said, why didn't I go to integrated schools?

881
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:38,000
I think I was in the 10th grade when we finally had integration.

882
01:08:38,000 --> 01:08:52,000
And again, my mother simply didn't trust me to be in a school with teachers who didn't want me there.

883
01:08:52,000 --> 01:09:06,000
And I remember so well when my friends went to my church, integrated, ramsy high school.

884
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:09,000
And Phillips, there were all kinds of problems.

885
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:14,000
But in those moments of desecrification, just as was the case with the University of Alabama,

886
01:09:14,000 --> 01:09:17,000
very decent whites were there, parents.

887
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:21,000
And they became violent. They threw things at these children.

888
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:24,000
You saw the worst of humanity.

889
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:29,000
And understandably, my parents did not want me being a part of that.

890
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:32,000
No. Even if the education was supposed to be better.

891
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:37,000
My parents who had been teachers knew was, if teachers don't want you there,

892
01:09:37,000 --> 01:09:40,000
you don't get the best education. You just don't.

893
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:42,000
Now, there were some decent people there, of course.

894
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:47,000
But how would you know who's willing to get beyond prejudice and just help a child?

895
01:09:47,000 --> 01:09:49,000
That was the issue.

896
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:53,000
Tell me about your effort to create the model of scholarship.

897
01:09:53,000 --> 01:09:55,000
And what that does.

898
01:09:55,000 --> 01:09:56,000
Sure.

899
01:09:56,000 --> 01:09:57,000
What that vision is.

900
01:09:57,000 --> 01:09:58,000
Sure.

901
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:03,000
When I went to the University of Illinois after graduating from Hampton,

902
01:10:03,000 --> 01:10:06,000
I noticed that, of course, there were no black faculty.

903
01:10:06,000 --> 01:10:12,000
And there were only several of us in mathematics, and others were not doing well.

904
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:17,000
And people didn't expect me to do well.

905
01:10:17,000 --> 01:10:21,000
I remember I tell my students this story all the time.

906
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:29,000
I earned an A-minus on a test in topology.

907
01:10:29,000 --> 01:10:35,000
And the professor wrote on my paper, you did surprisingly well.

908
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:38,000
Now, remember I said my mother was in English, and so I went up to a math class,

909
01:10:38,000 --> 01:10:40,000
and I said, why the adverb?

910
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:42,000
And he didn't know what I was talking about at first.

911
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:45,000
And I pointed to the word, he said, return red.

912
01:10:45,000 --> 01:10:47,000
And he said, well, it's because you're from a small school.

913
01:10:47,000 --> 01:10:48,000
No.

914
01:10:48,000 --> 01:10:51,000
It was at that point I remember that second grade experience.

915
01:10:51,000 --> 01:10:53,000
I could decide I'm a victim.

916
01:10:53,000 --> 01:10:55,000
The man doesn't expect me to do well.

917
01:10:55,000 --> 01:10:56,000
Let me get out of here.

918
01:10:56,000 --> 01:10:58,000
And I remember that same statement.

919
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:00,000
No time to be a victim.

920
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:03,000
Don't let this man define you.

921
01:11:03,000 --> 01:11:10,000
And by the end of the semester, he was feeling so guilty.

922
01:11:10,000 --> 01:11:15,000
Not just about the word, but about not telling me the truth.

923
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:19,000
The fact was he had never seen a black in a graduate course in mathematics.

924
01:11:19,000 --> 01:11:23,000
And everything he knew about blacks would suggest they would not do well.

925
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:25,000
And I didn't know.

926
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:29,000
In his class, but more important than that, he got to know me as a person.

927
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:30,000
And I got to know him.

928
01:11:30,000 --> 01:11:32,000
Who wasn't that he was a bad person.

929
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:36,000
We expect from people what we're accustomed to see.

930
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:38,000
And that was all it was.

931
01:11:38,000 --> 01:11:42,000
But all of that showed me that we had a problem.

932
01:11:42,000 --> 01:11:45,000
You don't have many blacks in math and science.

933
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:49,000
When I went around the country trying to find one predominantly white university

934
01:11:49,000 --> 01:11:52,000
that was educating at least 10 people a year.

935
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:56,000
And all of science engineering, there were gone who would go into grad school to find one.

936
01:11:56,000 --> 01:12:03,000
And fortunately, I had met Bob Mahal, who is not black, he's Jewish, and a philanthropist.

937
01:12:03,000 --> 01:12:09,000
And we had conversations about black males and he wanted to make a difference in that group.

938
01:12:09,000 --> 01:12:16,000
And we married the two ideas of black males, under-representation in science,

939
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:18,000
and started this program with that.

940
01:12:18,000 --> 01:12:20,000
And I towards seeing what can we do.

941
01:12:20,000 --> 01:12:27,000
Can we create a program that has those elements necessary to ensure that students of color

942
01:12:27,000 --> 01:12:32,000
would not only succeed but excel in science and engineering.

943
01:12:32,000 --> 01:12:37,000
And we were defining exceling as doing so well that they could go on and get PhDs

944
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:41,000
from the best universities in the country, an MD PhD.

945
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:48,000
And it has been an amazing journey since 1989.

946
01:12:48,000 --> 01:12:54,000
And now we have hundreds and hundreds who've actually earned PhDs, an MD PhDs.

947
01:12:54,000 --> 01:13:03,000
We actually now have students with those degrees on the medical faculties of Harvard and Stanford, Duke.

948
01:13:03,000 --> 01:13:08,000
Even you may be hopkin, you know, Michigan all over the country.

949
01:13:08,000 --> 01:13:10,000
And so the numbers are growing all the time.

950
01:13:10,000 --> 01:13:12,000
So it's a dream fulfilled.

951
01:13:12,000 --> 01:13:13,000
It really is.

952
01:13:13,000 --> 01:13:20,000
And for many scientists, it's the first time they've seen large numbers of students of color

953
01:13:20,000 --> 01:13:22,000
exceling in science.

954
01:13:22,000 --> 01:13:24,000
Not just the exception of one.

955
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:26,000
That's the idea.

956
01:13:26,000 --> 01:13:30,000
We've had an exceptional one since Tuskegee and George Washington cover.

957
01:13:30,000 --> 01:13:32,000
Now it's time to have many more.

958
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:37,000
And so working with the national academies on these issues,

959
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:43,000
I have had a chance to chair most recent committee and to look at what we're going to need to do to take the numbers to the next level.

960
01:13:43,000 --> 01:13:50,000
And all of that comes as a result of when you think about it, when I think about it,

961
01:13:50,000 --> 01:13:54,000
of the hope I got from those experiences as a child.

962
01:13:54,000 --> 01:13:59,000
And that the notion again, and I've never said it this way before,

963
01:13:59,000 --> 01:14:02,000
that just because it's this way doesn't mean it has to be this way.

964
01:14:02,000 --> 01:14:05,000
Now when we were doing the mile-haul,

965
01:14:05,000 --> 01:14:08,000
it never occurred to me to say that,

966
01:14:08,000 --> 01:14:13,000
and yet all those experiences from before,

967
01:14:13,000 --> 01:14:17,000
if we could move from my not being able to sit in a classroom with whites,

968
01:14:17,000 --> 01:14:22,000
to my being president of a definitely white university,

969
01:14:22,000 --> 01:14:25,000
from age 12 to age 40 and 30 years,

970
01:14:25,000 --> 01:14:31,000
why couldn't we move from having no blacks with Chisines and Science to having many?

971
01:14:31,000 --> 01:14:36,000
So it's amazing how one experience does inform another.

972
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:39,000
That's very interesting even to me.

973
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:43,000
That is really how I feel.

974
01:14:43,000 --> 01:14:46,000
Yes, yes.

975
01:14:46,000 --> 01:14:49,000
Thank you for all this, Jess.

976
01:14:49,000 --> 01:14:54,000
Let me invite you to reflect a little bit here as we close on

977
01:14:54,000 --> 01:14:57,000
how you take the measure of history,

978
01:14:57,000 --> 01:15:00,000
you look through, and you've thought so much about,

979
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:03,000
and the work you're doing now,

980
01:15:03,000 --> 01:15:06,000
and how you knit those two things together to define your working vision of your job.

981
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:10,000
You know, in 1963,

982
01:15:10,000 --> 01:15:15,000
only about 2% of African Americans had complete college.

983
01:15:15,000 --> 01:15:20,000
Today, we're moving to a 20%, 17%, 18%.

984
01:15:20,000 --> 01:15:24,000
But you didn't need a college education to get a good job.

985
01:15:24,000 --> 01:15:27,000
Today, you need more education.

986
01:15:27,000 --> 01:15:31,000
What was the civil rights movement really about?

987
01:15:31,000 --> 01:15:34,000
Well, in very basic terms,

988
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:41,000
it was about people wanting to have the opportunities that all other Americans have.

989
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:45,000
But it really is about more than opportunity for this reason.

990
01:15:45,000 --> 01:15:48,000
Today, people have the opportunity to go to college,

991
01:15:48,000 --> 01:15:50,000
and yet, lot don't.

992
01:15:50,000 --> 01:15:52,000
So what's missing here?

993
01:15:52,000 --> 01:15:58,000
It's about having families and communities that focus on education,

994
01:15:58,000 --> 01:16:01,000
and on values, and on dreams,

995
01:16:01,000 --> 01:16:06,000
and the connection between hard work and reaching the dreams.

996
01:16:06,000 --> 01:16:09,000
This is where we are challenged today.

997
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:12,000
Many families, black and white,

998
01:16:12,000 --> 01:16:17,000
don't necessarily know what they need to do to help their children

999
01:16:17,000 --> 01:16:20,000
to develop the skills they need, the values,

1000
01:16:20,000 --> 01:16:22,000
so they can get the education.

1001
01:16:22,000 --> 01:16:26,000
And without the education, they continue to be in the underclass.

1002
01:16:26,000 --> 01:16:29,000
And so for privileged people of any race,

1003
01:16:29,000 --> 01:16:32,000
all kinds of opportunities are available.

1004
01:16:32,000 --> 01:16:35,000
So for those of us in that top group, 25-30%,

1005
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:37,000
things are much better.

1006
01:16:37,000 --> 01:16:38,000
They really are.

1007
01:16:38,000 --> 01:16:40,000
And if we're not careful,

1008
01:16:40,000 --> 01:16:44,000
we forget about those at the bottom.

1009
01:16:44,000 --> 01:16:47,000
There is the challenge that we face

1010
01:16:47,000 --> 01:16:52,000
to not be duped into thinking these things don't matter anymore.

1011
01:16:52,000 --> 01:16:55,000
I would say race still matters,

1012
01:16:55,000 --> 01:16:58,000
but I would add on, I mean, it's concerned about poor white children

1013
01:16:58,000 --> 01:17:02,000
and as black children, that in either case,

1014
01:17:02,000 --> 01:17:05,000
unless somebody teaches those children to read well,

1015
01:17:05,000 --> 01:17:07,000
the future won't be bright.

1016
01:17:07,000 --> 01:17:09,000
That's the issue we face.

1017
01:17:09,000 --> 01:17:13,000
And history has taught us the focus on education and values

1018
01:17:13,000 --> 01:17:16,000
and how we can make all the difference in the world.

1019
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:17,000
Thanks, sir.

1020
01:17:17,000 --> 01:17:19,000
So generous to invite us here.

1021
01:17:19,000 --> 01:17:21,000
It's been a time with us. It's been great.

1022
01:17:21,000 --> 01:17:23,000
It has been a privilege for me. You are quite good.

1023
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:25,000
Both of you. Both of you. It's amazing.

1024
01:17:25,000 --> 01:17:26,000
It's amazing.

1025
01:17:26,000 --> 01:17:30,000
The videographer has such sensitivity, such, I mean, I felt him.

1026
01:17:30,000 --> 01:17:33,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

1027
01:17:33,000 --> 01:17:35,000
and the Smithsonian National Museum

1028
01:17:35,000 --> 01:17:39,000
of African-American history and culture.

